      "kind": "hook",
      "title": "Streamline Your Web Interactions",
      "narration": "Hey there, are you tired of manually handling HTTP requests in your Python code? Let me introduce you to the magic of the Requests library.",
      "start": 0,
      "end": 8.761,
      "startFrame": 0,
      "endFrame": 263,
      "matched": true
    },
    {
      "id": "beat-2",
      "kind": "concept",
      "title": "HTTP Requests",
      "narration": "HTTP requests are the bread and butter of web communication. They're how your browser talks to websites and gets information.",
      "start": 8.761,
      "end": 16.222,
      "startFrame": 263,
      "endFrame": 487,
      "matched": true
    },
    {
      "id": "beat-3",
      "kind": "concept",
      "title": "Requests Library",
      "narration": "The Requests library is like a Swiss Army knife for Python. It simplifies sending HTTP requests and handling responses, making your web interactions a breeze.",
      "start": 16.222,
      "end": 26.883,
      "startFrame": 487,
      "endFrame": 806,
      "matched": true
    },
    {
      "id": "beat-4",
      "kind": "concept",
      "title": "Python Code",
      "narration": "With Requests, you can write Python code that sends requests to web services, processes the responses, and even handle authentication.",
      "start": 26.883,
      "end": 34.863,
      "startFrame": 806,
      "endFrame": 1046,
      "matched": true
    },
    {
      "id": "beat-5",
      "kind": "how_it_works",
      "title": "Sending a Request",
      "narration": "You start by importing the Requests library into your Python script. Then, you use it to send a request to a web service, like getting data from a website.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "A",
        "B",
        "C"
      ],
      "start": 34.863,
      "end": 43.784,
      "startFrame": 1046,
      "endFrame": 1314,
      "matched": true
    },
    {
      "id": "beat-6",
      "kind": "how_it_works",
      "title": "Processing the Response",
      "narration": "Once the web service responds, Requests automatically parses the response and gives you access to the data, like the status code, headers, and the actual content.",
      "nodeIds": [
        "C",
        "D"
      ],
      "start": 43.784,
      "end": 53.825,
      "startFrame": 1314,
      "endFrame": 1615,
